<P>Yes, it did; but I name it to tell you a cir|cum&s;tance which attended it: we had in the hou&s;e an old man, an Italian, whom he always kept in the compt|ing-hou&s;e to copy his letters, and tran&s;late his Italian accompts, and for &s;uch other bu&s;ine&s;s as he employed him in; and they called him doctor: the &s;urgeon we had &s;ent for being in bed, did not come time enough, and he grew black and de&s;perately ill, which frighted me exceed|ingly; and when he &s;aw I was under a &s;urpri&s;e he <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;igns (for he could not &s;peak to be under&s;tood, he <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> bad) to call up the old Italian. When he came into the room, he held out his arm, and pointing at it with <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">
<PB N="203" REF="025384_0202_0FCCDD6756009180">
finger, every one might under&s;tand that he meant he &s;hould let him blood; upon which, immediately the old man called for things proper, and I found he had a lan|cet in his pocket. I a&s;ked him if he had been u&s;ed to it: he &s;aid, yes, Madam, I have let him blood &s;everal times before now. In a word, he opened a vein, and it gave him ea&s;e, and he recovered &s;oon after.</P>
